    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-06-25T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-06-25T11:00:00-05:00" n="560"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d560">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M)/7154: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-06-25T12:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 25, 1942—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>558. Your no. 684, June 10, 11 a.m.<note n="21" xml:id="d560fn21">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Offer of CNAC to transport metals is still receiving consideration. Your
                        no. 611, May 27.</item>
                    <pb facs="0669" n="659" xml:id="pg_659"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Project of making Chinese tin available to the Soviet Union by the
                        northwest route is under discussion with the Soviet authorities. Yin,
                        representative of the Chinese National Resources Commission, asserts
                        inability of the Chinese to transport tin or to do anything more than make
                        delivery at Kunming, but has offered to make cable inquiry. Department
                        therefore has noted with interest your comment that Chinese can and should
                        transport tin to point in northwest.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Department is gratified at progress made in shipment materials and hopes
                        that arrangements regarding bristles will now go forward, Department’s no.
                        537 June 20, 1 p.m.<note n="22" xml:id="d560fn22">Not printed.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Director Air Transport Project, BEW,<note n="23" xml:id="d560fn23">Board
                            of Economic Warfare.</note> desires regular reports air shipments from
                        China all commodities by both army and CNAC planes. Please instruct Consul
                        [at] Kunming report regularly including summary shipments already
                        made.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
